egacies since 1964 -- t9. The Deathblows to Authoritarian Rule. The Civil and Voting Rights Acts and National Party Reform, 1964-72 -- t10. Harnessing the Revolution? Three Paths Out of Dixie -- t11. Legacies and Lessons of the Democratized South -- tNotes -- tIndex -- tBackmatter0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe transformation of the American South--from authoritarian to democratic rule--is the most important political development since World War II. It has re-sorted voters into parties, remapped presidential elections, and helped polarize Congress. Most important, it is the final step in America's democratization. Paths Out of Dixie illuminates this sea change by analyzing the democratization experiences of Georgia, Mississippi, and South Carolina. Robert Mickey argues that Southern states, from the 1890s until the early 1970s, constituted pockets of authoritarian rule trapped within and sustained by a federal democracy. These enclaves--devoted to cheap agricultural labor and white supremacy--were established by conservative Democrats to protect their careers and clients. From the abolition of the whites-only Democratic primary in 1944 until the national party reforms of the early 1970s, enclaves were battered and destroyed by a series of democratization pressures from inside and outside their borders. Drawing on archival research, Mickey traces how Deep South rulers--dissimilar in their internal conflict and political institutions--varied in their responses to these challenges. Ultimately, enclaves differed in their degree of violence, incorporation of African Americans, and reconciliation of Democrats with the national party. These diverse paths generated political and economic legacies that continue to reverberate today. Focusing on enclave rulers, their governance challenges, and the monumental achievements of their adversaries, Paths Out of Dixie shows how the struggles of the recent past have reshaped the South and, in so doing, America's political development.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aDemocratizationvSouthern States. 0aDemocratizationzSouthern States. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / American Government / State.2bisacsh  aAfrican Americans.  aAmerican political development.  aBrown v. Board of Education.  aCivil Rights Act 1964.  aClemson College.  aDeep South.  aDixiecrats.  aGeorgia.  aHarry S. Truman.  aHerman Talmadge.  aJames Meredith.  aMississippi.  aNational Democratic Party.  aReconstruction.  aRepublicans.  aSmith v. Allwright.  aSouth Carolina.  aSouth.  aStates' Rights Party.  aU.S. Supreme Court.  aUniversity of Georgia.  aUniversity of Mississippi.  aVoting Rights Act 1965.  aWhite Citizens' Council.  aauthoritarian enclaves.  aauthoritarian rule.  ablack education.  ablack insurgency.  ablack politics.  ablack protest.  ademocracy.  ademocratic rule.  ademocratization.  adesegregation.  aeconomic development.  aelites.  afactional conflict.  aharnessed revolution.  aintraparty conflict.  amassive resistance.  aone-party rule.  aparty factionalism.  aparty reforms.  aparty-state capacity.  apartyгtate institutions.  apolitical authority.  apolitical culture.  apolitical development.  apolitical geography.  apresidential elections.  aracial equality.  aregime change.  asubnational authoritarianism.  asubnational democratization.  asuffrage.  avoting rights.  awhite primary.  awhite supremacy.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG and UP eBook Package 2000-2015z978311063872108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2015z9783110439687oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Histor